<pb n="3">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3><idref>Z300221389</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>PRIVATE SADNESS</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221389</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>PRIVATE SADNESS</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010023</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010023</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>PRIVATE SADNESS</mainhead><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1981</attpubn1><attpubn2>1981</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">Sitting here alone, in peace</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">With my private sadness</l>
<l ln="3        ">Bared of the acquirements</l>
<l ln="4        ">Of the mind's eye</l>
<l ln="5        ">Vision reversed, upended,</l>
<l ln="6        ">Seeing only the holdings</l>
<l ln="7        ">Inside the walls of me,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Feeling the roots that bind me,</l>
<l ln="9        ">To this mere human tree</l>
<l ln="10      ">Thrashing to free myself,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Knowing the success</l>
<l ln="12      ">Of these burstings</l>
<l ln="13      ">Shall be measured</l>
<l ln="14      ">By the fury</l>
<l ln="15      ">Of the fall</l>
<l ln="16      ">To eternal peace</l>
<l ln="17      ">The end of All.</l></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="4">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3><idref>Z300221390</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>LORCA</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221390</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>LORCA</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010024</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010024</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>LORCA</mainhead><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1981</attpubn1><attpubn2>1981</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<lb><pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">      Split ears of morning earth green now,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Love and death twisted in tree arms,</l>
<l ln="3        ">            Come love, throw out your nipple</l>
<l ln="4        ">to the teeth of a passing clown.</l></pdiv>
<lb><pdiv><l ln="5        ">Spit olive pits at my Lorca,</l>
<l ln="6        ">Give Harlem's king one spoon,</l>
<l ln="7        ">At four in the never noon.</l>
<l ln="8        ">Scoop out the croaker eyes</l>
<l ln="9        ">      of rose flavored Gypsies</l>
<l ln="10      ">Singing Garc&iacute;a,</l>
<l ln="11      ">In lost Spain's</l>
<l ln="12      ">Darkened noon.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="5">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3><idref>Z300221391</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>DEAR PEOPLE</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221391</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>DEAR PEOPLE</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010025</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010025</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>DEAR PEOPLE</mainhead><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1981</attpubn1><attpubn2>1981</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">We cut our teeth on oyster shells,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">We were suckled on father's milk,</l>
<l ln="3        ">So what?</l>
<l ln="4        ">Broken homes,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Don't cop out,</l>
<l ln="6        ">Buying diamonds</l>
<l ln="7        ">Off the backs of</l>
<l ln="8        ">South African Negroes</l>
<l ln="9        ">The wax bitches</l>
<l ln="10      ">Are well dressed tonight,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Dear people,</l>
<l ln="12      ">Let us</l>
<l ln="13      ">Eat jazz.</l></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="6">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3><idref>Z300221392</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>[THESE DAYS AND WEEKS]</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221392</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>[THESE DAYS AND WEEKS]</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010026</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010026</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>[THESE DAYS AND WEEKS]</mainhead><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1981</attpubn1><attpubn2>1981</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<lb><pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">These days and weeks</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">That cannot be found on any calendar,</l>
<l ln="3        ">These hours and minutes unknown to the clock,</l>
<l ln="4        ">When all those rusting ships of the past, long gone</l>
<l ln="5        ">To the bottom of life, guarding the sunken dreams</l>
<l ln="6        ">Cast up their sorrows to swell this grief with memory.</l></pdiv>
<lb><pdiv><l ln="7        ">Terror is around us both my soul. Nothing else will come.</l>
<l ln="8        ">I cannot describe the horrors, and worse, I cannot flee.</l>
<l ln="9        ">A wall is all.</l>
<l ln="10      ">I am hacked by knives I do not see, stung by stinging bee,</l>
<l ln="11      ">I can only bleed in silence, my pains are numb with admiration.</l></pdiv>
<lb><pdiv><l ln="12      ">Where do you keep them all, my soul? How long can you stand?</l>
<l ln="13      ">What question is this being asked, can humans ever know?</l>
<l ln="14      ">Mad teeth are in the forms of man and chew my love to bits,</l>
<l ln="15      ">And I can do nothing, my soul, but wait their clawing cut,</l>
<l ln="16      ">      Asking only that my flesh holds</l>
<l ln="17      ">      &amp; my anguished mind's reassurance in surprise,</l>
<l ln="18      ">      &amp; my love survive these brutal enigmas,</l>
<l ln="19      ">That I please you, my Soul ... if only you alone.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="7">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3><idref>Z300221393</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>AWE</mainhead> <attbytes>1Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221393</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>AWE</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010027</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010027</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>AWE</mainhead><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>1Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1981</attpubn1><attpubn2>1981</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">At confident moments, thinking on Death</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">I tell my soul I am ready and wait</l>
<l ln="3        ">While my mind knows I quake and tremble</l>
<l ln="4        ">At the beautiful Mystery of it.</l></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="8">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3><idref>Z300221394</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>PICASSO'S BALCONY</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221394</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>PICASSO'S BALCONY</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010028</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010028</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>PICASSO'S BALCONY</mainhead><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1981</attpubn1><attpubn2>1981</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<p ln="[1]"><firstl>Pale morning light,</firstl> dying in shadows, loving the earth in midday rays, casting blue to skies in rings, sowing powder trails across balconies. Hung in evening to swing gently, on shoulders of time, growing old, yet swallowing events of a thousand nights of dying and loving, all blue. Gone to that tomb, hidden in cubic air, breathing sounds of sorrow.</p>
<p ln="[2]">Crying love rising from the lips of wounded flowers, wailing, sobbing, breathing uneven sounds of sorrow, lying in wells of earth, throbbing, covered with desperate laughter, out of cool angels, spread over night. Dancing blue images, shades of blue pasts, all yesterdays, tomorrows, breaking on pebbled bodies, on sands of blue and coral, spent.</p>
<p ln="[3]">Life lying heaped in mounds, with volcano mouth tops, puckered, open, sucking in atoms of air, sprinkling in atoms of air, coloring space, with flecks of brilliance, opaline glistening, in eyes, in flames.</p>
<p ln="[4]">Blue flames burning, on rusty cliffs, overlooking blue seas, bluish. In sad times, hurt seabirds come to wail in ice white wind, alone, and wail in starlight wells, cold pits of evening, and endings, flinging rounds of flame sheeted balls of jagged bone, eaten, with remains of torn flowers, overwhelming afterthoughts, binding loves, classic pains, casting elongated shadows, of early blue.</p>
<p ln="[5]">Stringing hours together in thin melodic lines, wrapped around the pearl neck of morning, beneath the laughter, of sad sea birds.</p></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="9">
<div3>
