<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3><idref>Z300221437</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>[ALL THOSE SHIPS THAT NEVER SAILED]</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221437</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>[ALL THOSE SHIPS THAT NEVER SAILED]</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010062</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010062</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>[ALL THOSE SHIPS THAT NEVER SAILED]</mainhead><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1981</attpubn1><attpubn2>1981</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<lb><pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">All those ships that never sailed</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">The ones with their seacocks open</l>
<l ln="3        ">That were scuttled in their stalls ...</l>
<l ln="4        ">Today I bring them back</l>
<l ln="5        ">Huge and intransitory</l>
<l ln="6        ">And let them sail</l>
<l ln="7        ">Forever.</l></pdiv>
<lb><pdiv><l ln="8        ">All those flowers that you never grew&mdash;</l>
<l ln="9        ">      that you wanted to grow</l>
<l ln="10      ">The ones that were plowed under</l>
<l ln="11      ">      ground in the mud&mdash;</l>
<l ln="12      ">Today I bring them back</l>
<l ln="13      ">And let you grow them</l>
<l ln="14      ">Forever.</l></pdiv>
<lb><pdiv><l ln="15      ">All those wars and truces</l>
<l ln="16      ">Dancing down these years&mdash;</l>
<l ln="17      ">All in three flag&hyphen;swept days</l>
<l ln="18      ">Rejected meaning of God&mdash;</l></pdiv>
<lb><pdiv><l ln="19      ">My body once covered with beauty</l>
<l ln="20      ">Is now a museum of betrayal.</l>
<l ln="21      ">This part remembered because of that one's touch</l>
<l ln="22      ">This part remembered for that one's kiss&mdash;</l>
<l ln="23      ">Today I bring it back</l>
<l ln="24      ">And let you live forever.</l></pdiv>
<lb><pdiv><l ln="25      ">I breathe a breathless I love you</l>
<l ln="26      ">And move you</l>
<l ln="27      ">Forever,</l></pdiv>
<lb><pdiv><l ln="28      ">Remove the snake from Moses' arm ...</l>
<pb n="56">
<l ln="29      ">And someday the Jewish queen will dance</l>
<l ln="30      ">Down the street with the dogs</l>
<l ln="31      ">And make every Jew</l>
<l ln="32      ">Her lover.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="57">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3><idref>Z300221438</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>[MY MYSTERIES CREATED FOR ME]</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221438</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>[MY MYSTERIES CREATED FOR ME]</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010063</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010063</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>[MY MYSTERIES CREATED FOR ME]</mainhead><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1981</attpubn1><attpubn2>1981</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">MY MYSTERIES CREATED FOR ME</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">BY GOD ARE UNKNOWN TO</l>
<l ln="3        ">ME, YET I LIVE EACH ONE</l>
<l ln="4        ">PERFECTLY, GOD IS MY GREEN&hyphen;</l>
<l ln="5        ">EYED ONE, WHOSE POWER IS</l>
<l ln="6        ">ENDLESS. I ASK GOD,</l>
<l ln="7        ">OH GOD ... TO THE COWARD, GIVE A HORSE</l>
<l ln="8        ">THAT HE MAY FLEE GOD FOREVER,</l>
<l ln="9        ">GIVE CAIN NO FORGIVENESS</l>
<l ln="10      ">FOR WHAT WAS DONE, I ASK GOD,</l>
<l ln="11      ">MY GREEN&hyphen;EYED ONE, BEFORE THIS</l>
<l ln="12      ">EARTH STOPS SPINNING, THINK OF ME.</l>
<l ln="13      ">REMEMBER, I AM HERE TOO, MY GREEN&hyphen;</l>
<l ln="14      ">EYED ONE WHOSE POWER IS ENDLESS, AFTER</l>
<l ln="15      ">WHAT WAS DONE TO YOU, WHAT FORGIVENESS ...</l>
<l ln="16      ">O GOD, MY GREEN&hyphen;EYED ONE</l>
<l ln="17      ">COME UPON THE EARTH</l>
<l ln="18      ">AND STRIKE THE GLOBE</l>
<l ln="19      ">WITH YOUR WRATH, FOR</l>
<l ln="20      ">WHAT HAS DIED IN THE SUN.</l>
<l ln="21      ">O GOD, MY GREEN&hyphen;EYED ONE,</l>
<l ln="22      ">PUT YOUR SHARP STARS IN</l>
<l ln="23      ">THE SKY. SEND ORION</l>
<l ln="24      ">THE HUNTER STAR TO HUNT</l>
<l ln="25      ">THE KILLERS OF THE DREAM,</l>
<l ln="26      ">TO HUNT THE SLAYERS OF</l>
<l ln="27      ">THE DIVINE INCUNABULA, O</l>
<l ln="28      ">MY GREEN&hyphen;EYED ONE, BEFORE THIS EARTH STOPS</l>
<l ln="29      ">SPINNING.</l></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="58">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3><idref>Z300221439</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>OREGON</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221439</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>OREGON</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010064</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010064</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>OREGON</mainhead><volhead>The Ancient Rain: Poems, 1956&ndash;1978 (1981)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1981</attpubn1><attpubn2>1981</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<firstl><l ln="1        ">You are with me Oregon,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Day and night, I feel you, Oregon.</l>
<l ln="3        ">I am Negro. I am Oregon.</l>
<l ln="4        ">Oregon is me, the planet</l>
<l ln="5        ">Oregon, the State Oregon, Oregon.</l>
<l ln="6        ">In the night, you come with bicycle wheels,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Oregon you come</l>
<l ln="8        ">With stars of fire. You come green.</l>
<l ln="9        ">Green eyes, hair, arms,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Head, face, legs, feet, toes</l>
<l ln="11      ">Green, nose green, your</l>
<l ln="12      ">Breast green, your cross</l>
<l ln="13      ">Green, your blood green.</l>
<l ln="14      ">Oregon winds blow around</l>
<l ln="15      ">Oregon. I am green, Oregon.</l>
<l ln="16      ">You are mine, Oregon. I am yours,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Oregon. I live in Oregon.</l>
<l ln="18      ">Oregon lives in me,</l>
<l ln="19      ">Oregon, you come and make</l>
<l ln="20      ">Me into a bird and fly me</l>
<l ln="21      ">To secret places day and night.</l>
<l ln="22      ">The secret places in Oregon,</l>
<l ln="23      ">I am standing on the steps</l>
<l ln="24      ">Of the holy church of Crispus</l>
<l ln="25      ">Attucks St. John the Baptist,</l>
<l ln="26      ">The holy brother of Christ,</l>
<l ln="27      ">I am talking to Lorca. We</l>
<l ln="28      ">Decide the Hart Crane trip, home to Oregon</l>
<l ln="29      ">Heaven flight from Gulf of</l>
<l ln="30      ">Mexico, the bridge is</l>
<l ln="31      ">Crossed, and the florid black found.</l></poem>
</div3>
