<pb n="3">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3 align="l"><idref>Z300221555</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>I HAVE FOLDED MY SORROWS</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221555</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>I HAVE FOLDED MY SORROWS</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010076</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010076</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>I HAVE FOLDED MY SORROWS</mainhead><volhead>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1965</attpubn1><attpubn2>1965</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">I have folded my sorrows into the mantle of summer night,</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Assigning each brief storm its allotted space in time,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Quietly pursuing catastrophic histories buried in my eyes.</l>
<l ln="4        ">And yes, the world is not some unplayed Cosmic Game,</l>
<l ln="5        ">And the sun is still ninety&hyphen;three million miles from me,</l>
<l ln="6        ">And in the imaginary forest, the shingled hippo becomes</l>
<l ln="7        ">          the gay unicorn.</l>
<l ln="8        ">No, my traffic is not with addled keepers of yesterday's</l>
<l ln="9        ">          disasters,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Seekers of manifest disembowelment on shafts of yesterday's</l>
<l ln="11      ">          pains.</l>
<l ln="12      ">Blues come dressed like introspective echoes of a journey.</l>
<l ln="13      ">And yes, I have searched the rooms of the moon on cold</l>
<l ln="14      ">          summer nights.</l>
<l ln="15      ">And yes, I have refought those unfinished encounters.</l>
<l ln="16      ">          Still, they remain unfinished.</l>
<l ln="17      ">And yes, I have at times wished myself something different.</l></pdiv>
<lb>
<pdiv>
<l ln="18      ">The tragedies are sung nightly at the funerals of the poet;</l>
<l ln="19      ">The revisited soul is wrapped in the aura of familiarity.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="4">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3 align="l"><idref>Z300221556</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>AFRICAN DREAM</mainhead> <attbytes>2Kb</attbytes><volhead>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221556</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>AFRICAN DREAM</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010077</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010077</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>AFRICAN DREAM</mainhead><volhead>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>2Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1965</attpubn1><attpubn2>1965</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">In black core of night, it explodes</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Silver thunder, rolling back my brain,</l>
<l ln="3        ">Bursting copper screens, memory worlds</l>
<l ln="4        ">Deep in star&hyphen;fed beds of time,</l>
<l ln="5        ">Seducing my soul to diamond fires of night.</l>
<l ln="6        ">Faint outline, a ship&hyphen;momentary fright</l>
<l ln="7        ">Lifted on waves of color,</l>
<l ln="8        ">Sunk in pits of light,</l>
<l ln="9        ">Drummed back through time,</l>
<l ln="10      ">Hummed back through mind,</l>
<l ln="11      ">Drumming, cracking the night.</l>
<l ln="12      ">Strange forest songs, skin sounds</l>
<l ln="13      ">Crashing through&mdash;no longer strange.</l>
<l ln="14      ">Incestuous yellow flowers tearing</l>
<l ln="15      ">Magic from the earth.</l>
<l ln="16      ">Moon&hyphen;dipped rituals, led</l>
<l ln="17      ">By a scarlet god,</l>
<l ln="18      ">Caressed by ebony maidens</l>
<l ln="19      ">With daylight eyes,</l>
<l ln="20      ">Purple garments,</l>
<l ln="21      ">Noses that twitch,</l>
<l ln="22      ">Singing young girl songs</l>
<l ln="23      ">Of an ancient love</l>
<l ln="24      ">In dark, sunless places</l>
<l ln="25      ">Where memories are sealed,</l>
<l ln="26      ">Burned in eyes of tigers.</l></pdiv>
<lb>
<pdiv>
<l ln="27      ">Suddenly wise, I fight the dream:</l>
<l ln="28      ">Green screams enfold my night.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="5">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3 align="l"><idref>Z300221557</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>WALKING PARKER HOME</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221557</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>WALKING PARKER HOME</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010078</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010078</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>WALKING PARKER HOME</mainhead><volhead>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1965</attpubn1><attpubn2>1965</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">Sweet beats of jazz impaled on slivers of wind</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">Kansas Black Morning/ First Horn Eyes/</l>
<l ln="3        ">Historical sound pictures on New Bird wings</l>
<l ln="4        ">People shouts/ boy alto dreams/Tomorrow's</l>
<l ln="5        ">Gold belled pipe of stops and future Blues Times</l>
<l ln="6        ">Lurking Hawkins/ shadows of Lester/ realization</l>
<l ln="7        ">Bronze fingers&mdash;brain extensions seeking trapped sounds</l>
<l ln="8        ">Ghetto thoughts/ bandstand courage/ solo flight</l>
<l ln="9        ">Nerve&hyphen;wracked suspicions of newer songs and doubts</l>
<l ln="10      ">New York altar city/ black tears/ secret disciples</l>
<l ln="11      ">Hammer horn pounding soul marks on unswinging gates</l>
<l ln="12      ">Culture gods/ mob sounds/ visions of spikes</l>
<l ln="13      ">Panic excursions to tribal Jazz wombs and transfusions</l>
<l ln="14      ">Heroin nights of birth/ and soaring/ over boppy new ground.</l>
<l ln="15      ">Smothered rage covering pyramids of notes spontaneously</l>
<l ln="16      ">          exploding</l>
<l ln="17      ">Cool revelations/ shrill hopes/ beauty speared into</l>
<l ln="18      ">          greedy ears</l>
<l ln="19      ">Birdland nights on bop mountains, windy saxophone</l>
<l ln="20      ">          revolutions</l>
<l ln="21      ">Dayrooms of junk/ and melting walls and circling vultures/</l>
<l ln="22      ">Money cancer/ remembered pain/ terror flights/</l>
<l ln="23      ">Death and indestructible existence</l></pdiv>
<lb>
<pdiv>
<l ln="24      ">In that Jazz corner of life</l>
<l ln="25      ">Wrapped in a mist of sound</l>
<l ln="26      ">His legacy, our Jazz&hyphen;tinted dawn</l>
<l ln="27      ">Wailing his triumphs of oddly begotten dreams</l>
<l ln="28      ">Inviting the nerveless to feel once more</l>
<l ln="29      ">That fierce dying of humans consumed</l>
<l ln="30      ">In raging fires of Love.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>
<pb n="6">
<div3>
<poem>
<comhd3 align="l"><idref>Z300221558</idref><collection>1 2</collection>

<somhead><somauth>Kaufman, Bob<sombiog>1193</sombiog></somauth><mainhead>AFTERWARDS, THEY SHALL DANCE</mainhead> <attbytes>3Kb</attbytes><volhead>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></somhead><reflink></reflink><comcitn><TY>DATA</TY><ID>Z300221558</ID><A1>Kaufman, Bob</A1><T1>AFTERWARDS, THEY SHALL DANCE</T1><PBL>New Directions</PBL><Y1>1981</Y1><T2>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)</T2><T3>Literature Online</T3></comcitn></comhd3>
<attribs><attpoet>Kaufman, Bob</attpoet><attidref>J3010079</attidref></attribs>
<newatts><attidref>J3010079</attidref><attdbase>Twentieth-Century American Poetry</attdbase><attdbase>Twentieth-Century African-American Poetry</attdbase><attpubl>New Directions</attpubl><atttitle><mainhead>AFTERWARDS, THEY SHALL DANCE</mainhead><volhead>Solitudes Crowded with Loneliness (1965)<publish>, New Directions</publish></volhead></atttitle><attsize>3Kb</attsize><attperi>Twentieth-Century 1900-1999</attperi><attpubn1>1965</attpubn1><attpubn2>1965</attpubn2><attview></attview><attview></attview><attautid>1193</attautid></newatts>
<pdiv><firstl><l ln="1        ">In the city of St. Francis they have taken down the statue of</l></firstl>
<l ln="2        ">         St. Francis,</l>
<l ln="3        ">And the hummingbirds all fly forward to protest, humming</l>
<l ln="4        ">         feather poems.</l></pdiv>
<lb>
<pdiv>
<l ln="5        ">Bodenheim denounced everyone and wrote. Bodenheim had</l>
<l ln="6        ">         no sweet marijuana dreams,</l>
<l ln="7        ">Patriotic muscateleer, did not die seriously, no poet love to</l>
<l ln="8        ">         end with, gone.</l></pdiv>
<lb>
<pdiv>
<l ln="9        ">Dylan took the stone cat's nap at St. Vincent's, vaticaned</l>
<l ln="10      ">         beer, no defense;</l>
<l ln="11      ">That poem shouted from his nun&hyphen;filled room, an insult to the</l>
<l ln="12      ">         brain, nerves,</l>
<l ln="13      ">Save now from Swansea, white horses, beer birds, snore</l>
<l ln="14      ">         poems, Wales&hyphen;bird.</l></pdiv>
<lb>
<pdiv>
<l ln="15      ">Billie Holiday got lost on the subway and stayed there</l>
<l ln="16      ">         forever,</l>
<l ln="17      ">Raised little peace&hyphen;of&hyphen;mind gardens in out of the way</l>
<l ln="18      ">         stations,</l>
<l ln="19      ">And will go on living in wrappers of jazz silence forever,</l>
<l ln="20      ">         loved.</l></pdiv>
<lb>
<pdiv>
<l ln="21      ">My face feels like a living emotional relief map, forever wet.</l>
<l ln="22      ">My hair is curling in anticipation of my own wild gardening.</l></pdiv>
<lb>
<pdiv>
<l ln="23      ">Poor Edgar Allan Poe died translated, in unpressed pants,</l>
<l ln="24      ">         ended in light,</l>
<l ln="25      ">Surrounded by ecstatic gold bugs, his hegira blessed</l>
<l ln="26      ">         by Baudelaire's orgy.</l></pdiv>
<pb n="7">
<lb>
<pdiv>
<l ln="27      ">Whether I am a poet or not, I use fifty dollars' worth</l>
<l ln="28      ">         of air every day, cool.</l>
<l ln="29      ">In order to exist I hide behind stacks of red and blue poems</l>
<l ln="30      ">And open little sensuous parasols, singing the nail&hyphen;in&hyphen;</l>
<l ln="31      ">         the&hyphen;foot song, drinking cool beatitudes.</l></pdiv></poem>
</div3>
